A. Business Understanding¶

The dataset selected to perform this analysis presents the data based on certain driving behavior. The data was collected using a smartphone while driving. The raw data was translated into the Earth coordinate system because the smartphone and the car may have different coordinate systems. The smartphone was held in the same direction during the ride. Later the mathematical features were extracted such as mean, variance, skewness, kurtosis, median, min, max, quantile 10 to 90, and coefficient of variation, leading to the prediction and evaluation of various traffic and driving behaviors. The data was collected by Farbod about one and a half year ago with his own car using Sensor-Recorder application which is suitable for saving the data of sensors such as acceleration, gyroscope, proximity, gravity, and linear acceleration in the smartphone.

Predicting whether the driver has a tendency to drive aggressively or non-aggressively is the main task of this data. This data is of wide interest to insurance companies, police, and city governments. Predicting whether the driving is aggressive or not, from the data which is taken while driving can be useful to regulate the cost of insurance, produce a safety index, or even reduce the fuel consumption. For this prediction task to be considered useful to these third parties, like police, the accuracy should be as good as it can be, preferably better than 85% as it will be used to predict the fault of respective drivers involved in the accident and will affect people who are involved in these accidents. In the case where Insurance companies are using this algorithm, our prediction task should have at least 90% accuracy as it will affect the cost of the insurance for the customers of insurance companies.

There are different movement categories, which are described as acceleration, brake, speed bumper, turn, lane changing and background. Having the coordinate of the car to be driven aligned with the Y-axis, the acceleration, brake, speed bumper are mostly affected by mean and variance of X- and Y-axis of the acceleration, while the turns and the lane changing are mostly affected by the mean and variance of X- and Z- axis of the gyroscope.

Another important issue is about the type of behavior of each movement: aggressive or non-aggressive. To be more specific, aggressive or nonaggressive driving behavior is highly dependent on the driving style and it's not logical to assume a constant amount for a variable such as acceleration to label it as aggressive or nonaggressive but in general, there are some conditions that cause aggressiveness such as when one drives at 100 km/h speed and immediately stops the car so this action results in aggressive brake.

# counts muber of movements 
cols = ['MeanAccX', 'MeanAccY', 'VarAccX', 'VarAccY', 'MeanGyrX', 'MeanGyrZ', 'VarGyrX', 'VarGyrZ']
def plot_bars(df, cols):
    for col in cols:
        fig = plt.figure(figsize=(6,6)) 
        ax = fig.gca()  
        counts = df[col].value_counts() 
        counts.plot.bar(ax = ax, color = 'blue') 
        ax.set_xlabel(col) 
        ax.set_ylabel('Number of ' + col )
        plt.show()

plot_cols = ['Movement', 'Ag_Non']
plot_bars(df, plot_cols)

Above two visualizations are for the types of movements which are considered in the driving dataset. The first plot shows the total number of each type of movement. As seen clearly, the dataset contains a lot of readings taken for turns, the highest number of data collected is for aggressive turns and the lowest number of data is collected for non-aggressive braking. The second plot shows the total number of all types of movements for an aggressive and non-aggressive category. We can see that readings taken while driving non-aggressively are higher than readings taken for aggressive driving.

Matrix plot¶

The following matrix plot shows the correlation between the features. The relationship level is indicated with colors and numbers where the lighter color, the better correlation is presented. As we can observe, there is very less correlation between the features. The matrix plot does not show any number over 0.4 (orange color). The lowest correlation, -0.52 (black color), is shown between MeanAccX and MeanGyrZ. The lack of correlation is a consequence of different sensors in smartphones for collecting data such as Gyroscope and Acceleration. The Gyroscope collects the rotational velocity of the car in each direction separately and the Acceleration collects the change in speed per second in each direction. Assuming the condition of the two sensors mentioned above, it is somehow illogical to relate these two features with each other because they are working separately. This is exactly what this correlation matrix plot shows us, that the features do not have much correlation between them.

Distributions¶

This shows that the X-axis is taken into account just during the turns, or lane changing. This is correlated with the Y-axis which displays straight movements.

The distribution of VarAccY and VarAccX are both quite skewed to the left and not-multimodal. Given the skew and the fact that there are no values less than or equal to zero, a Gaussian transformation might be appropriate. The rest of the plots show that the majority of the values are close to zero.

Histograms¶

The histograms below indicate the frequency of each feature based on their amount in two categories, aggressive (red) and non-aggressive (blue). Comparing the results to those obtained in the above, the distribution is more or less similar. Also, it does appear that the non-aggressive and aggressive data overlap with each other. The plot for the 'MeanAccX' which is mean acceleration in the X-direction shows that there is a lot of overlap in the aggressive and non-aggressive data, but the data value for aggressive where there is no overlap is higher, which should definitely be the case, as aggressive acceleration would mean higher values. This can be very helpful, especially, when predicting the driving. For instance, we can consider the values excluding the overlap region and decide aggressive driving for values outside the overlap and non-aggressive for data that have overlap.

Also, as seen in the 3rd plot, which is 'VarAccX', the aggressive driving values completely overlap the data values for non-aggressive driving. This is interesting as it shows us that a value of 1 for 'VarAccX' doesn't necessarily mean that the driver was driving aggressively because the same value shows us that the driving was non-aggressive as there is an overlap. Such readings visualizations are very helpful for predictions in cases which are borderline.

In the case of 6th plot of 'MeanGyrZ', it is seen that the there is an overlap in the values of aggressive and non-aggressive values in the center, but there is no overlap for values near the two edges. so, the values in the range -0.70 to -0.40 and 0.45 to 0.70 would be considered aggressive and those in between would be non-aggressive.

Interpretation of t-SNE results¶

As we can see in the plot above, the input data having 8 features is reduced to a 2-dimensional data, which implies that it just has 2 features now. There are clusters of data formed based on the similarity between the points. So, the points in the same color belong to the same classes when t-SNE calculates the similarity and classifies them into different classes. We don't get any statistical information from the output data, we can visualize the input data points though, which was not possible for data having 8 dimensions.

Explanation of t-SNE dimensionality reduction methods¶

t-Distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (t-SNE) is a non-linear technique for dimensionality reduction. When the dataset has many features it becomes difficult to understand or explore the relationships between the features as it is very difficult to visualize this high dimensional data. In such a case, we implement dimensionality reduction to convert this data to a 2 dimensional or 3-dimensional data in order to visualize it easily.

The algorithms start by calculating the probability of similarity of points in high-dimensional space and in the corresponding low-dimensional space. The similarity of points is calculated as the conditional probability that a point A would choose point B as its neighbor if neighbors were picked in proportion to their probability density under a Gaussian distribution which is centered at A. The difference between these conditional probabilities is then minimized in higher as well as lower dimension. This helps to represent data properly in lower dimensions.

t-Distributed stochastic neighbor embedding (t-SNE) minimizes the divergence between the distribution that measures pairwise similarities of the input data features and a distribution that measures pairwise similarities of the corresponding low-dimensional data points. It finds patterns in the data by identifying observed clusters based on the similarity of data points with multiple features. The input features, however, are not identifiable after doing dimensionality reduction using t-SNE so it is not possible to infer anything from the lower-dimensional data obtained from t-SNE. Thus, this process is mainly used for exploring and visualizing high dimensional data.

Above information about t-SNE is obtained from https://www.datacamp.com/community/tutorials/introduction-t-sne
